{
  "text": "The LT2 strain originally used to analyze the pgi (atbR):: Tn10 insertion produces very little 38 , which in turn limits the ATR [CITATION_1] . Therefore, we suspected that the pgi mutation suppressed the acid-sensitive phenotype of rpoS mutants. To test this theory, the pgi (atbR)::Tn10 insertion was analyzed for its effect on an rpoS \u03e9 strain (UK1) and an rpoS null mutant. At pH 3, the rpoS mutant JF2690 proved to be extremely acid sensitive after 60 min of adaptation, while the rpoS pgi (atbR) mutant (JF2731) was very acid tolerant even when unadapted (Fig. 1) . The effect of pgi (atbR) on the ATR of an rpoS \u03e9 strain was to increase tolerance even in unadapted cells. Subsequently, a pgi mutation obtained from the Salmonella Genetic Stock Center was also shown to suppress the acid-sensitive phenotype of an rpoS mutant (Fig. 1) .",
